@generic{Wright2002a,
   abstract = {Phenotypic plasticity is commonly assessed by comparing phenotypes of plants grown under a range of environmental conditions. However, it is well known that many phenotypic traits vary as a function of growth and development, and that growth and development rates themselves are highly plastic. 'Passive plasticity' (variation in a trait as a consequence of environmentally induced variation in growth) is distinguished from 'ontogenetic plasticity' (environmentally induced variation in the ontogenetic trajectory of a trait) and conclusions regarding phenotypic plasticity may differ dramatically if ontogenetic changes in phenotypic expression are not considered. Studies that demonstrate that phenotypic plasticity is not evenly expressed throughout the organism's lifetime, and that there are periods during development when changes in environmental conditions may not elicit plastic responses or may elicit plastic responses that differ from those expressed at other points in development, are reviewed. In conclusion, studies that do not follow phenotypes throughout the entire course of growth and development may greatly over- or underestimate the degree of plasticity, or even the very nature of the plastic response expressed.},
